  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law in the United States, money laundering can result in significant criminal penalties, including:\n\n1. Potential Prison Sentences\n- Up to 20 years in federal prison per offense\n- Potentially longer sentences for aggravated cases\n- Sentences can be consecutive if multiple charges apply\n\n2. Financial Penalties\n- Substantial monetary fines\n- Often up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved in the transaction\n\n3. Asset Forfeiture\n- Government can seize assets connected to money laundering activities\n- Potential loss of property, bank accounts, and other financial instruments\n\n4. Additional Consequences\n- Criminal record\n- Loss of professional licenses\n- Potential immigration consequences for non-citizens\n\n5. Civil Penalties\n- Potential additional civil monetary penalties\n- Possible lawsuit from government agencies\n\nThe specific penalties depend on factors like:\n- Amount of money involved\n- Specific nature of the offense\n- Whether it's a first or repeat offense\n- Involvement of other criminal activities\n\nThese penalties are typically prosecuted under statutes like the Bank Secrecy Act and Money Laundering Control Act.\n\nNote: This information is general legal overview and should not be considered specific legal advice. Actual outcomes can vary based on individual circumstances.",
